"M:" en comments "M corresponds to the semiotic triad (sign S, being or interpreter B and thing, object or referent T). In addition to this particular meaning M refers to any triadic symmetry between concepts like, for example, past, present, future in [conjugations](https://intlekt.io/?comments=E%3A.-M%3A.O%3AM%3A.-t.-%27).\nFrom a tradition beginning with Aristotle with his treatise called *On interpretation* the Prince of philosophers is the first to distinguish between the written or spoken symbol (sign), the state of mind of a subject (being) and the thing denoted by a speech (thing). This initial tripartite concept was further developed by Latin philosophers of the Middle Ages under the concepts of: vox (sign), conceptus (being) and res (thing). Later, the same semiotic triangle was refined by Charles S. Peirce, an American philosopher of the 19th century, who differentiated the foundation of the sign, the interpretant, and the object."
